composition: Copper (81%),Tin (11%),Lead(0.9%),Zinc (2.7%),Iron and aluminum present but not determined. Not assayed, arsenic, antimony, phosphorus.
remarks: N.B.: These particulars enclosed in a letter dated 25th Sept. 1944, from Mr. W. A. Seaby, Keeper of the City Museum and Art Gallery, Birmingham, to the Secretary Smith of [...] London. description: Discovered by workmen digging a drainage inspection box immediately to the south of the front door of "Seaward", The Ridings, East Preston (TQ 068018). Found 18 inches deep in clay mould. Found July, 1954.,Late Bronze Age palstave with stop-ridge and loop. Two raised ribs below and almost at right angles to stop-ridge. Both flanges on one side damaged.
remarks: One of nine implements found at "Seaward" by workmen. This, and one small fragment of a palstave were brought to my notice at the Museum; extensive enquiries, however, failed to trace any others which were reputed to have been 'sold to a dealer for sixpence'; etc. The building firm concerned, also, was most un-cooperative. The workmen were questioned as to the appearance of the others and from their description it appears to have been a hoard of eight palstaves and one socketed axe.

description: Dimensions: L 151.3mm; Wbl.e 35.6mm; Wbt 19.5mm; max B bt 5.5mm; T sep 14.5mm; B st. 31.7mm; Blp 10.2mm,Typology: crisp body angles to butt end, but each with facet, just below end; fg. crests mainly rounded to flat and undulating; underside of st. bevelled - reverse one more regular; constriction at top of blade not defined by neat side bevels; blade angles crisp; septum angles fairly crisp, corners little rounded, end little bowed; both septums offset to right at bottom,Manufacture: low fairly narrow stump of cg. fl. on loop - rounded with some battering; above loop and on central part of reverse side low broad flat-topped cg. fl with hammer marks, but no  sign lpg.; fully removed elsewhere on sides, where some suggestion of hammer marks, also on lower blade; very slight hollows immediately beneath stops on faces - probably cg. flaws; some irregularity on fg. insides - as cast,Condition: butt end a broken surface - untampered with; blade edge more or less intact, but not sharp, possibly due to det.; band of diagonal grmks. up on blade face - pres. modern but no diff. colour,Attached Material: butt soil traces, especially on butt end and under lp.

Stovin (c) the,Context: possibly 1a. Hoard,Label/Markings: formerly marked 1938.3-5.5 by mistake from the haft it was mounted in.

Circumstances: only support for this at present in the comparison between POA 87 and the 'Axholm' hoard palstave illustrated by Banks (b) - both in general stype and length (6 1/2 inches). Banks, and formerly Stukeley, had in fact mistaken the provenance of the hoard known as 'Isle of Axholm' which was found before 1847 by the servants of Mr. G. Healey while digging for firewood on Burringham Moor, in Burringham parish, on the opposite seide of the Trent (c)

description: The flanges taper from the prominent stop ridge towards the butt: on both faces of the palstave is a well-defined [tongue?] shaped ridge which protrudes from the stop ridge towards the cutting edge. The fin down the middle of both sides (casting mark) has not been entirely removed. Both the cutting edge and the butt have been considerably hammered. In places the bright surface of the bronze indicates "polishing up" by finder.
remarks: Found in 1934 in digging port hole in yard of a small holding known as "Mount Pleasant" c. 600 feet above sea level. "Mount Pleasant" is not named on 6"0-S. LXXX S.W., but it is the building 530 yards SSE of Curland Church, and, as the crow flies, only 680 yards NNW of the "Beacon" of Castle Neroche (see Proc. Som. Arch. Soc. XLIX ii 23-53). The impt. was found by D.G. Dicks, the owner of the building, at a depth of 3 ft.

remarks: Letter from Miss (?) F.A. Sherland, Ilminster, May 19, 1877 to Thos. Codrington, Esq. 10 Montague Villes, Richmond Hill, Surrey.  "I have this day forwarded to your address the Battle Axes...they were dug up in 'Winterhay Green' which was a small common in the parish of Ilminster, when my brother was having his allotment drained. There were 2 ornaments of gold...It was rolled up in a [bundle?] but when opened it was a long strip of gold, about, about 1/4 of an inch in width, with a kind of crook at the end to fasten with. It was a very large piece and weighed about the weight of 2 guineas; if I recollect right there were 2 similar pieces."

description: Dimensions: L 173.5mm; We 74.9mm; Wbt 25.5mm; Bfg. 32.7mm; Bst (middle) 29.3mm; Tsep 7.7mm; Wt. 590.9 gms,Typology: slightly irregular bev. across fg. tops on sep.; one sep. little wider than other - both curved between in cross-sec., with rounded angles; fg. and stop crests neat rounded - no distinct bevels; stops little depressed in centre; short fg. extensions onto bl. with flattened crests tending to splay at bases; midribs low-rounded bumps with at crisp bevels - one extends virt. to edge bev., other higher, but as short as fg. extensions; slides slightly bowed in cross-sec.,Manufacture: cg. fl. remains as very broad low rounded bump - less pronounced on other side, virt. all trace removed on bl. sides, with some hammer rippling; dimples generally over surface - hammer marks or moulding? Swallow hole in end of one sep., depression in other; e. bevs. little diffuse - assoc. hammermarks,Condition: most of blade edge irregular - probably from chipping of patina, but one large chip def. anc. with patina intact; patina frag. also in one butt depression - irreg line probably original 2 or 3 small gougings of patina - probably recent - including one blade angle, forming facet; short intact stretches of blade edge suggest once fairly sharp,Attached material: chalky fawn 'dust' adhering in parts; some stained orange brown matrix also
remarks: Circumstances: Found Winter 1978/9; actual field from which recovered not remembered by finer, but Susan Limbrey was able to match clayey soil deposits adhering to the axe with soil from Pits Field - the only clayey one in the vicinity; GR based on centre of field. (a)
